{"title_page": "Bastille discography", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist          = [[Bastille (band)|Bastille]]\n| Image           = Bastille 2015-7.jpg\n| Caption         = Bastille's lead singer, Dan Smith, performing at Lollapalooza in 2015\n| Alt             = Lead vocalist Dan Smith holding a microphone\n| Studio          = 3\n| Compilation     = 1\n| Music videos    = 22\n| EP              = 7\n| Singles         = 21\n| B-sides         = 8\n| Option          = 4\n| Option name     = Mixtapes\n| 1Option         = 8\n| 1Option name    = Remixes\n}}\n\nThe [[discography]] of [[Bastille (band)|Bastille]], a British [[indie pop]] band, consists of three [[studio album]]s, seven [[extended play]]s, twenty-one [[Single (music)|single]]s and twenty-two [[music video]]s. Originally a solo project by Dan Smith, Bastille was formed in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/mn0002825814|title=Bastille \u2013 Biography|last=Buchanan|first=John D.|publisher=[[Allmusic|AllMusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref> The band released its debut single \"Flaws\" / \"Icarus\" in July 2011 on the [[independent record label]] Young and Lost Club. An extended play titled ''Laura Palmer'' followed later that year. The critical success of the EP and extensive touring brought the group to the attention of [[Virgin Records]], which signed them in December 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emimusic.com/blog/2011/virgin-records-welcomes-new-signings-bastille-and-eric-prydz/# |title=Virgin Records welcomes new signings Bastille and Eric Prydz |publisher=[[Virgin Records]]. [[EMI]] |date=1 December 2011 |accessdate=31 March 2013 |archivedate=29 April 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429173649/http://www.emimusic.com/blog/2011/virgin-records-welcomes-new-signings-bastille-and-eric-prydz/ |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nBastille released their debut studio album, ''[[Bad Blood (Bastille album)|Bad Blood]]'', in March 2013. The album reached number one on the [[UK Albums Chart|United Kingdom]] albums chart and the top ten of the [[Irish Albums Chart|Irish]] albums chart.<ref name=\"UK-albums\"/><ref name=\"IRL\"/> It has been [[List of music recording certifications|certified]] double platinum by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) and gold by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA).<ref name=\"BPI\"/> The band released six singles from the album: \"[[Overjoyed (Bastille song)|Overjoyed]]\", \"[[Bad Blood (Bastille song)|Bad Blood]]\", \"[[Flaws (song)|Flaws]]\", \"[[Pompeii (Bastille song)|Pompeii]]\", \"[[Laura Palmer (song)|Laura Palmer]]\", and \"[[Things We Lost in the Fire (song)|Things We Lost in the Fire]]\", with \"Pompeii\" peaking at number two on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and topping the charts in Ireland and Scotland.<ref name=\"IRL\"/><ref name=\"UK-singles\"/> \"Pompeii\" reached number five on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and has been certified 5\u00d7 Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].<ref name=\"RIAA\"/>\n\nIn November 2013, Bastille released compilation album ''All This Bad Blood'', which features songs from the extended edition of ''Bad Blood'' and their mixtapes, as well as two new songs. The band has released two singles from the album: \"[[Oblivion (Bastille song)|Oblivion]]\" and \"[[Of the Night]]\", a mash-up of the songs \"[[The Rhythm of the Night (song)|The Rhythm of the Night]]\" by [[Corona (group)|Corona]] and \"[[Rhythm Is a Dancer]]\" by [[Snap!]].\n\nOn 8 December 2014, Bastille released their third mixtape, ''[[VS. (Other People's Heartache, Pt. III)]]'', which included collaborations with [[Haim (band)|Haim]] (\"Bite Down\"), [[Angel Haze]] (\"Weapon\"), [[MNEK]] (\"bad_news\"), [[Grades (producer)|GRADES]] (\"Torn Apart\"), and [[Rag'n'Bone Man]] and [[Skunk Anansie]] (\"Remains\").\n\n==Albums==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with selected chart positions and certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:22em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.9em;font-size:90%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br><ref name=\"UK-albums\">{{cite web | url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/7574/bastille | title=Bastille | publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] | accessdate=28 October 2018 | type=select \"Albums\" tab}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.9em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref name=\"AUS\">{{cite web | url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Bastille | title=Discography Bastille | publisher=Hung Medien | work=australian-charts.com | accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.9em;font-size:90%;\"| [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|AUT]]<br><ref name=\"AUT\">{{cite web | url=http://austriancharts.at/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Bastille | title=Discographie Bastille | publisher=Hung Medien | work=austriancharts.at | accessdate=14 March 2014 | language=German}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.9em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL]]<br><ref name=\"BEL-FL\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Bastille | title=Discographie Bastille | publisher=Hung Medien | work=ultratop.be | accessdate=14 March 2014 | language=Dutch}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.9em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br><ref name=\"CAN-albums\">{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/music/bastille/chart-history/canadian-albums | title=Bastille \u2013 Chart History: Billboard Canadian Albums | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | accessdate=28 October 2018}}